480","1425–Male":"1425–Afdød","1435–1480":"1435–1480","1435–1496":"1435–1496","1426–1450":"1426–1450","1451–1470":"1451–1470","1394–1482":"1394–1482","1451":"1451","1450":"1450","1482":"1482","1394":"1394","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1426":"1426","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1446":"1446","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1496":"1496","1506":"1506","1417":"1417","Syleham, Suffolk, England":"Syleham, Suffolk, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1425–":"1425–Overleden","1415–1506":"1415–1506","1420–1480":"1420–1480","1425–Male":"1425–Overleden","1435–1480":"1435–1480","1435–1496":"1435–1496","1426–1450":"1426–1450","1451–1470":"1451–1470","1394–1482":"1394–1482","1451":"1451","1450":"1450","1482":"1482","1394":"1394","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1426":"1426","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1446":"1446","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1496":"1496","1506":"1506","1417":"1417","Syleham, Suffolk, England":"Syleham, Suffolk, England","Kent, England":"Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1425–":"1425–Deceased","1415–1506":"1415–1506","1420–1480":"1420–1480","1425–Male":"1425–Deceased","1435–1480":"1435–1480","1435–1496":"1435–1496","1426–1450":"1426–1450","1451–1470":"1451–1470","1394–1482":"1394–1482","1451":"1451","1450":"1450","1482":"1482","1394":"1394","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1426":"1426","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1446":"1446","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1496":"1496","1506":"1506","1417":"1417","Syleham, Suffolk, England":"Syleham, Suffolk, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Clark","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>clerk</i>, <i>clark</i> ‘clerk, cleric, writer’ (Old French <i>clerc</i>; see   Clerc  ). The original sense was ‘man in a religious order, cleric, clergyman’. As all writing and secretarial work in medieval Christian Europe was normally done by members of the clergy, the term <i>clerk</i> came to mean ‘scholar, secretary, recorder, or penman’ as well as ‘cleric’. As a surname, it was particularly common for one who had taken only minor holy orders. In medieval Christian Europe, clergy in minor orders were permitted to marry and so found families; thus the surname could become established.","Irish (Westmeath, Mayo): in Ireland the English surname was frequently adopted, partly by translation for <i>Ó Cléirigh</i>; see   Cleary  .","Americanized form of Dutch   De Klerk   or Flemish   De Clerck   or of variants of these names, and possibly also of French   Clerc  . Compare   Clerk   2 and   De Clark  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Clarke","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Clark  .","History: This name was brought independently to New England by many bearers from the 17th century onward. Nicholas Clarke was one of the founders of Hartford, CT (coming from Cambridge, MA with Thomas Hooker) in 1635."]},{"name":"Clerk","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Jacques.","English: variant of   Clark  .","Americanized form of French   Clerc   and perhaps also of the Dutch and Flemish cognates   De Klerk   and   De Clerck   or of variants of these names. Compare   Clark   3."]},{"name":"Clerkin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Liam, Brendan, Dympna, Seamus.","Irish (Monaghan): from an Irish pet form of English <i>clerk</i> ‘cleric’ (Irish <i>cléireach</i>), see   Clark  . Alternatively, an Anglicized form of <b>Ó Cléireacháin</b>, ‘descendant of little cleric’, an Irish diminutive of the word. See also   McClurkin  , an Antrim surname from <i>Mac Cléirchín</i> ‘son of little cleric’."]},{"name":"Calarco","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Rocco, Angelo, Carmelo, Fausto, Nunziato, Salvatore.","Italian (southern): probably a nickname derived from Greek <i>kalē archē</i> ‘good beginning’. Compare   Clark   4."]},{"name":"Clerc","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alain, Odette, Sebastien, Serge.","French: occupational or status name for a member of a minor religious order or for a scholar, Old French <i>clerc</i>, from Late Latin <i>clericus</i>, from Greek <i>klērikos</i>, a derivative of <i>klēros</i> ‘inheritance, legacy’, with reference to the priestly tribe of Levites (see   Levy  ) ‘whose inheritance was the Lord’. In medieval Christian Europe, clergy in minor orders were permitted to marry and so found families; thus the surname could become established. In the Middle Ages it was virtually only members of religious orders who learned to read and write, so that the term <i>clerc</i> later came to denote any literate man, a scholar (hence its modern meaning ‘scribe, secretary’ or ‘clerk’). Compare   Leclerc  ."]},{"name":"Clarkson","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): patronymic from   Clark  ."]}]},{"name":"Lewis","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form, since the Middle Ages, of the French name   Louis .  In modern use it is also in part a transferred use of the surname derived from this given name, or from Anglicized forms of Gaelic <i>Mac Lughaidh</i> ‘son of  <b>Lughaidh</b> ’  or Welsh Llewelyn ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lewys","meanings":["form, since the Middle Ages, of the French name   Louis .  In modern use it is also in part a transferred use of the surname derived from this given name, or from Anglicized forms of Gaelic <i>Mac Lughaidh</i> ‘son of  <b>Lughaidh</b> ’  or Welsh Llewelyn ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":30,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol